{"parse":{"title":"Geopiety","pageid":24321121,"revid":813047412,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Geopiety</b> is a term for \"the belief and worship of powers behind nature or the human environment\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> It was coined by the American geographer <a href=\"/wiki/John_Kirtland_Wright\" title=\"John Kirtland Wright\">John Kirtland Wright</a>.\n</p><p>The term \"geopiety\" comes from a combination of the <a href=\"/wiki/Greek_language\" title=\"Greek language\">Greek</a> root <i>geo</i>, for earth, and the <a href=\"/wiki/Latin_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Latin language\">Latin</a> root \"<a href=\"/wiki/Pietas_(virtue)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Pietas (virtue)\">pietas</a>\". As Wright explained when coining the term, geopiety is meant to refer to \"emotional piety aroused by awareness of terrestrial diversity of the kind of which geography is also a form of awareness\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-w251_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-w251-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>One example of geopiety can be found in the works of American preacher <a href=\"/wiki/Jonathan_Edwards_(theologian)\" title=\"Jonathan Edwards (theologian)\">Jonathan Edwards</a>:\n</p>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r856303468\">.mw-parser-output .templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 40px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote .templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style><blockquote class=\"templatequote\"><p>He that is traveling up a very high mountain, if he goes on climbing, will at length get to that height and eminence as at last not only to have his prospect vastly large, but he will get above clouds and winds, and where he will enjoy a perpetual serenity and calm. This may encourage Christians constantly and steadfastly to climb the Christian hill.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>That high towers or other high places are commonly smitten with thunder, and mountainous places more subject to terrible thunder and lightning, shows how that pride and self-exaltation does particularly excite God's wrath.<sup id=\"cite_ref-w251_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-w251-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Geopiety&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Religion_and_geography\" title=\"Religion and geography\">Religion and geography</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Geopiety&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Dijkink, Gertjan (2006). \"When Geopolitics and Religion Fuse: A Historical Perspective\". <i>Geopolitics</i>. <b>11</b> (2): 194. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1080/14650040600598403\">10.1080/14650040600598403</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Geopolitics&amp;rft.atitle=When+Geopolitics+and+Religion+Fuse%3A+A+Historical+Perspective&amp;rft.volume=11&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.pages=194&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1080%2F14650040600598403&amp;rft.aulast=Dijkink&amp;rft.aufirst=Gertjan&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGeopiety\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-w251-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-w251_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-w251_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Wright, 251.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Edwards, 68.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Edwards, 91.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Bibliography\">Bibliography</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Geopiety&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Bibliography\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation book\">Edwards, Jonathan (1948).  Perry Miller, ed. <i>Images or shadows of divine things</i>. Westport, Connecticut: Greenwood Press. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-8371-6952-6\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-8371-6952-6\">0-8371-6952-6</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Images+or+shadows+of+divine+things&amp;rft.place=Westport%2C+Connecticut&amp;rft.pub=Greenwood+Press&amp;rft.date=1948&amp;rft.isbn=0-8371-6952-6&amp;rft.aulast=Edwards&amp;rft.